Full Website With Admin Panel and CSV Message Storage

PHP Responsive Landing Page with Admin Panel
We can build a compact PHP website that stores data in a CSV file (no database) and includes an admin panel to view submitted messages. In this approach, user input (from a contact/order form) is saved to messages.csv using PHP’s file functions
stackoverflow.com
. A simple login form (password alitpreed0909) grants access to the admin page, which reads the CSV using fgetcsv(). The front-end uses modern HTML/CSS and a touch of JavaScript for responsiveness and interactivity
developer.mozilla.org
. The visible text employs persuasive marketing copy – for example, highlighting our location “Opposite Al Khairat Supermarket” with home delivery – and includes a bold call-to-action (CTA) like “Call Now: 090 268 5622” to encourage customers
park.edu
blog.hubspot.com
.
Key Features
Flat-file storage (CSV): Using PHP’s file routines, form data (name and message) is appended as a CSV row (e.g. via fputcsv()) and later read with fgetcsv(). This avoids using a database
stackoverflow.com
.
Admin login: A simple login form checks the hard-coded password "alitpreed0909". Upon success, we set $_SESSION['loggedin'] to display the admin panel.
Responsive design: We use CSS Flexbox/Grid and media queries so the page looks good on any device. As MDN notes, “Responsive web design (RWD) is a web design approach to make web pages render well on all screen sizes and resolutions”
developer.mozilla.org
.
JavaScript enhancements: A bit of JS handles form validation and any interactive effects (e.g. fade-in animations) to improve user experience.
Marketing copy & CTA: The page content uses persuasive language and clear CTAs. For example, we might list benefits (“Convenient location… Home delivery… Friendly service”) and then prompt the visitor to “Call Now: 090 268 5622”. Such calls-to-action encourage visitors to take action
blog.hubspot.com
. Persuasive copywriting – “using influential words to compel the audience to take a specific action”
park.edu
 – helps boost engagement and conversions.
Sample Code
Below is an example of the PHP/HTML/CSS code. The first block (index.php) is the landing page with a contact form. Submitted data is saved to messages.csv. The second block (admin.php) is the password-protected admin panel that lists all submitted messages.
<?php
// index.php
// Handle form submission: save name, message, and timestamp to CSV
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $name = htmlspecialchars($_POST['name']);
    $message = htmlspecialchars($_POST['message']);
    $time = date('Y-m-d H:i:s');
    $fp = fopen('messages.csv', 'a');         // Open CSV file for appending
    fputcsv($fp, array($name, $message, $time));
    fclose($fp);
}
?>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Transit Services (Opp. Al Khairat Supermarket)</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <style>
    /* Responsive, modern CSS styling */
    body { margin: 0; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; }
    header { background: #0066cc; color: #fff; padding: 40px 20px; text-align: center; }
    header h1 { margin: 0; font-size: 2.5em; }
    header p { font-size: 1.2em; }
    section { padding: 20px; max-width: 600px; margin: auto; }
    ul { list-style: square; margin: 10px 0 20px; padding-left: 20px; }
    input, textarea { width: 100%; padding: 10px; margin: 5px 0 15px; box-sizing: border-box; }
    button { background: #0099ff; color: white; border: none; padding: 10px 20px; font-size: 1em; cursor: pointer; }
    button:hover { background: #007acc; }
    @media(max-width: 600px) {
      header h1 { font-size: 1.8em; }
    }
  </style>
  <script>
    // Simple client-side form validation
    function validateForm() {
      var name = document.getElementById('name').value.trim();
      if (name === '') {
        alert('Please enter your name.');
        return false;
      }
      return true;
    }
  </script>
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Transit (Opp. Al Khairat Supermarket)</h1>
    <p>Fast Home Delivery Service &ndash; Call Now:</p>
    <p><strong>090 268 5622</strong></p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>Why Choose Us?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Convenient location opposite Al Khairat Supermarket</li>
      <li>Reliable home delivery right to your door</li>
      <li>Friendly staff and best prices guaranteed</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Call us now to place your order!</strong></p>

    <h2>Contact Form</h2>
    <p>Have questions or need a quick order? Send us a message!</p>
    <form method="post" onsubmit="return validateForm();">
      <label for="name">Name:</label><br>
      <input type="text" id="name" name="name" placeholder="Your Name" required><br>
      <label for="message">Message:</label><br>
      <textarea id="message" name="message" placeholder="Your Message or Order Details" required></textarea><br>
      <button type="submit">Send Message</button>
    </form>
  </section>
</body>
</html>
<?php
// admin.php
session_start();
$correct_pass = 'alitpreed0909';

// Handle login submission
if (isset($_POST['pass'])) {
    if ($_POST['pass'] === $correct_pass) {
        $_SESSION['loggedin'] = true;
    } else {
        echo '<p style="color:red;">Incorrect password.</p>';
    }
}

// If not logged in, show the login form
if (!isset($_SESSION['loggedin'])) {
    echo '<h2>Admin Login</h2>';
    echo '<form method="post">
            <input type="password" name="pass" placeholder="Enter Password">
            <button type="submit">Login</button>
          </form>';
    exit;
}

// Logged in: read and display messages from CSV
echo "<h2>Submitted Messages</h2>";
echo "<table border='1' cellpadding='5'><tr><th>Name</th><th>Message</th><th>Time</th></tr>";
if (($fp = fopen('messages.csv', 'r')) !== FALSE) {
    while (($row = fgetcsv($fp)) !== FALSE) {
        // Each $row is an array: [name, message, time]
        echo "<tr><td>{$row[0]}</td><td>{$row[1]}</td><td>{$row[2]}</td></tr>";
    }
    fclose($fp);
}
echo "</table>";
This code illustrates a simple PHP-based site with a marketing landing page and password-protected admin panel. All data (messages) are stored in a CSV file as flat text
